</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">N<sup>o</sup> 19</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">M<sup>r</sup> Chaboillez when he was preparing for his departure was not so fortunate as I was several useful trifles having been pilfered from him among which was the Girth of his Saddle<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">On the North side we lodged with our Old friend the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Black Cat</span> whom we found as usual civil and compaisant Yet he knew we had nothing left to give him in return.  He is actually one of the best Indians in that quarter.  The things which we had left in his charge were found safe and in good order<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  He even gave me a Horse on Credit the payment to be sent him in the fall<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This was an extraordinary degree of confidence from a Mandane.  We were short of Tobacco for the journey &#8212; but he assisted us all in his power.  That herb at this Early season having not come to maturity they make use of the blossoms which they collect and dry before the fire as necessity requires<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This afternoon the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Old Crane</span> with his Young men set out for the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Orignal</span> Mountain<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>bout this time a mandane who was watching on the top of his hut h<span class="AddHand-editors">[allowed]</span> out that the asseneboines were stealing the white peoples horses, meaning ours<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  In an instant the Village was in an uproar and all the men armed and on horseback determined to secure</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">the</p>

